{{Other uses|Liahona (disambiguation)}} [[File:Liahona.jpg|thumb|A 21st-century artistic representation of the Liahona]] According to the [[Book of Mormon]] and other [[Latter Day Saint movement]] sources, the '''Liahona''' ({{IPAc-en|ˌ|l|iː|ə|ˈ|h|oʊ|n|ə}})<ref>[http://www.lds.org/scriptures/bofm/pronunciation "Book of Mormon Pronunciation Guide"], lds.org (retrieved 2012-02-25), [[Wikipedia:IPA for English|IPA]]-ified from «lē´a-hō´na»</ref> is a brass ball that operated as a type of [[compass]] with two spindles. One of the spindles was said to point the direction [[Lehi (Book of Mormon)|Lehi]] and his party should travel after their escape from [[Jerusalem]], but it only worked when they were faithful. The Book of Mormon states that the Liahona also contained periodic written instructions from God. According to some sources, the Liahona was among the Book of Mormon artifacts [[Joseph Smith]] said were found with the [[golden plates]].<ref>{{Citation | last=Lapham | first=<nowiki>[La]</nowiki>Fayette | title=Interview with the Father of Joseph Smith, the Mormon Prophet, Forty years Ago. His Account of the Finding of the Sacred Plates | journal=Historical Magazine <nowiki>[second series]</nowiki> | volume=7 | year=1870 | pages=306–308 | url= http://en.wikisource.org/w/index.php?title=Historical_Magazine_%28second_series%29/Volume_7/May_1870/Interview_with_the_Father_of_Joseph_Smith&oldid=314358 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last=Salisbury | first=Katharine Smith | author-link=Katharine Smith Salisbury | date=April 10, 1895 | editor-last=Walker | editor-first=Kyle R. | title=Katharine Smith Salisbury's Recollections of Joseph's Meetings with Moroni | journal=BYU Studies | volume=41 | issue=3 | publication-date=2002 | pages=13 | url=https://byustudies.byu.edu/content/katharine-smith-salisburys-recollections-josephs-meetings-with-moroni | format= }}</ref>
==In the Book of Mormon== In the [[Book of Mormon]], the Liahona was found one morning at [[Lehi (Book of Mormon)|Lehi]]'s tent door. It is described as a round brass ball of "curious workmanship" with "two spindles," one of which indicated the direction that his party should travel ({{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=1 Nephi|chapter=16|verse=10}}). It is sometimes referred to as a compass, although the context makes it clear that it did not function like a [[magnetic compass]]. On occasion there was also writing on the ball that displayed additional instructions from God ({{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=1 Nephi|chapter=16|verse=26|range=-29}}). Using the Liahona, Lehi and his party were directed through the wilderness and across the ocean to the Americas. The Liahona worked "according to the faith and diligence" ({{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=1 Nephi|chapter=16|verse=28}}) with which they heeded its direction, and ceased functioning at times when the members of the party demonstrated a loss of faith in God's commandments, notably when [[Nephi, son of Lehi|Nephi's]] brothers rebelled against Lehi during their ocean crossing ({{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=1 Nephi|chapter=18|verse=12}}).
The only place in the Book of Mormon where the word "Liahona" is used is in the [[Book of Alma]], when [[Alma the Younger|Alma]], speaking to his son [[Helaman]], explains "our fathers called it Liahona, which is, being interpreted, a compass" ({{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=37|verse=38}}). Alma tells his son that "it is as easy to give heed to the word of Christ ... to eternal bliss, as it was for our fathers to give heed to this compass ... to the promised land" ({{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=37|verse=44}}).
==Meaning of the word ''Liahona''== According to the Book of Mormon, the word ''Liahona'' means "a compass" ({{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=37|verse=38}}). Latter-day Saint scholar [[Hugh Nibley]] also provided two additional possibilities for the meaning based on perceived Hebrew roots. He attributed the theory that it refers to a "queen bee" to a Hebrew University scholar named Shunary, and added his own speculation that ''Liyahhona'' might be translated "To God is the guidance." <ref>[[Hugh Nibley|Nibley, Hugh]]. Teachings of the Book of Mormon, Semester 1, p.216. [[Covenant Communications]] (2004). {{ISBN|978-1-59156-571-0}}</ref>
Jonathan Curci suggested that the word means "the direction of the Lord".<ref name = curci>Jonathan Curci, "Liahona: 'The Direction of the Lord': An Etymological Explanation", ''[[Journal of Book of Mormon Studies]]'' '''16'''(2) (2007): 60–67.</ref>
