{{Infobox company | name = Suncore Photovoltaics | logo = File:Suncorelogo.png | type = | slogan = | foundation = | location = [[Albuquerque]], New Mexico, USA | key_people = | num_employees = | parent = | products = [[Solar energy]] – [[Concentrator photovoltaics|CPV systems]] | homepage = {{URL|http://www.suncoreus.com/}} }}
'''Suncore Photovoltaic Technology Company Limited''' ("Suncore") is a [[solar energy]] company that specializes in [[concentrator photovoltaics]] (CPV), an emerging [[Photovoltaics|photovoltaic]] (PV) technology. The company manufactures, develops, and finances CPV systems for ground mounted applications. Its products include CPV solar power systems, receivers, trackers and turnkey service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=134197394|title=Suncore Photovoltaic Technology Co., Ltd.: Private Company Information - Businessweek|work=Businessweek.com}}</ref>
==History==
Suncore Photovoltaics Technology Co, Ltd, was founded in 2010 as a joint-venture company by Chinese LED manufacturer San'an Optoelctronics Co, Ltd and U.S. [[semiconductor]] manufacturer EMCORE Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pv-tech.org/news/emcore_sanan_create_suncore_joint_venture_to_develop_manufacture_distribute|title=Emcore, San'an create Suncore joint venture to develop, manufacture, distribute CPV gear in China - PV-Tech|work=pv-tech.org}}</ref> In 2013, San’an became the sole owner of Suncore by purchasing stocks from Emcore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/Soitec-SunPower-and-Suncore-The-Last-CPV-Vendors-Standing|title=Soitec, SunPower and Suncore: The Last CPV Vendors Standing |website=greentechmedia.com|date=2014-10-29|accessdate=2016-12-07}}</ref>
In 2013 Suncore acquired [[Zenith Solar]], the creator of a combined heat and power (CHP) technology which allows for the production of both electricity and hot water in a single system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.semiconductor-today.com/news_items/2013/OCT/SUNCORE_151013.shtml|title=CPV module maker Suncore acquires Israel-based ZenithSolar|work=semiconductor-today.com}}</ref>
==Operations== Suncore's manufacturing capacity is around 300&nbsp;[[megawatt]]s (MW) with its manufacturing facility of over {{convert|2000000|ft2|m2}} in China. In addition to system manufacturing, Suncore also supplies the solar receiver to labs and manufacturers around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/suncore-photovoltaic-technology|title=Suncore Photovoltaic Technology|work=crunchbase.com}}</ref> Suncore has a portfolio of 120&nbsp;MW of CPV systems deployed worldwide, including the [[Concentrator photovoltaics#List of large CPV systems|largest CPV power plant]] in Golmud, China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greentechmedia.com/articles/read/Soitec-SunPower-and-Suncore-The-Last-CPV-Vendors-Standing|title=Soitec, SunPower and Suncore: The Last CPV Vendors Standing|work=greentechmedia.com}}</ref>
